DataElement.preferredDefinition: The route of administration of the procedure.

DataElementConcept.preferredName: Procedure Domain Procedure Route of Administration
DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to procedure._The means of entry through which the procedure is taken into the body.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to procedure.

Concepts.definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to procedure.

Property.preferredDefinition: The means of entry through which the procedure is taken into the body.

Concepts.definition: The means of entry through which the procedure is taken into the body.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: An organizational header for concepts representing mostly abstract entities.

DataElementConcept.changeDescription: 2021-6-10 ak Released per governance approval.; 8-23-18 Created as part of the CDISC mapping task; tt.

ValueDomain.preferredName: CDISC SDTM Route of Administration Terminology Type
ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: Terminology codelist used with Route of Administration within the Clinical Data Interchange Standards Consortium Study Data Tabulation Model._Something distinguishable as an identifiable class based on common qualities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration through the nose and into the stomach, usually by means of a tube.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug through the nose and into the stomach, usually by means of a tube.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug by the way of the nose. This often results in systemic action of the agent due to absorption through the nasal mucosa. The richly supplied vascular nature of the nasal mucosa coupled with its high drug permeation makes the nasal route of administration attractive for many drugs, including proteins and peptides.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug by the way of the nose. This often results in systemic action of the agent due to absorption through the nasal mucosa. The richly supplied vascular nature of the nasal mucosa coupled with its high drug permeation makes the nasal route of administration attractive for many drugs, including proteins and peptides.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration through perfusion liquid.

Concepts.definition: Administration through perfusion liquid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug directly upon the larynx.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug directly upon the larynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to bathe or flush open wounds or body cavities.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug by bathing or flushing open wounds, body cavities or surfaces.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Ion transfer of topical solution into the epidermis and mucous membranes of body by continuous direct current. Can be used for local and systemic drug delivery. Concept does not refer to ion exchange, air ionization, and phonophoresis.

Concepts.definition: Ion transfer of topical solution into the epidermis and mucous membranes of body by continuous direct current. Can be used for local and systemic drug delivery. Concept does not refer to ion exchange, air ionization, and phonophoresis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the vitreous body of the eye.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the vitreous body of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the bladder.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the urinary bladder.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the vertebral column.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the vertebral column. High therapeutic ratio is based on drug delivery directly to central nervous system sites of action.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the nasal or periorbital sinuses.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug through the nasal sinuses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the lungs or its bronchi.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance in the form gas, aerosol, emulsion, or liquid (during partial and tidal liquid ventilation), or fine powder into the lung, often with systemic action. Method limitations: insufficient drug delivery to peripheral lung regions, the inability to quantify the actually administered dose, and non-homogeneous distribution.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the prostate gland.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the prostate gland.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the pleura.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the pleural cavity. The intrapleural drug administration usually results in both local and systemic drug action.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the peritoneal cavity.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug via injection or infusion of a substance into the peritoneum, where it is absorbed by the lining.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the pericardium.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the pericardium. Intrapericardial application of therapeutic agents provides a strategy for site-specific treatment of heart or coronary diseases. The magnitude of the local advantage depends on substance exchange between the local and the blood compartments and on substance elimination from these compartments.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration into the parenchyma of an organ.

Concepts.definition: Administration into the parenchyma of an organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration into the palate.

Concepts.definition: Administration into the palate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the ovary.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the ovary or ovaries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the marrow of the bone.

Concepts.definition: Administration within the marrow of the bone.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the eye.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the eye. Intraocular drugs are almost always used for their local effects.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a lymph node.

Concepts.definition: Administration within a lymph node.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a muscle.

Concepts.definition: Intramuscular injection is a route of drug administration via injection into muscle tissue. Aqueous or oleaginous solutions and emulsions or suspensions may be administered. Absorption rates, delay in availability of the drug to the systemic circulation, and duration of effect are perfusion-limited, depend on molecular size of the agent, volume, and osmolarity of the drug solution, fat content of the injection site, and patient physical activity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the meninges (the three membranes that envelope the brain and spinal cord).

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within meningeal membranes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the marrow cavity of a bone.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the marrow cavity of a bone. The essential premise for intraosseous administration is a functioning medullary cavity. The route is considered reasonably safe and permits rapid achievement of satisfactory plasma concentrations of therapeutic agent. The route is used for blood transfusion or fluid therapy when other routes are awkward, as in neonates.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the lymph.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the lymphatic system: into the lymph nodes or/and the lymph vessels.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the lumen of a tube.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the cavity or channel of a tubular structure or tubular organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within or introduced directly into a localized lesion.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within or introduced directly into a localized lesion. Method allows to achieve high concentration of the agent in the lesion and delay drug release in systemic circulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration into the jejunum.

Concepts.definition: Administration into the jejunum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a ventricle.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug directly into a cerebral ventricle, commonly using a reservoir. This allows a more even distribution of drug through the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and is particularly useful in the treatment of certain types of cancers.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within or into a vein or veins over a sustained period of time.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within or into a vein or veins over a sustained period of time. A slow, continuous drip avoids excessively high transient peak plasma levels.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug directly into circulation via a vein or veins over a time duration of less than or equal to 30 minutes. Method results in 100% bioavailability of the agent due to an absence of the absorption phase. FDA CDER (HL7) numeric code: 0138

Concepts.definition: A volume of drug intended to be administered into a vein at a relatively fast rate. The volume of drug and the rate of administration are specified.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within or into a vein or veins.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within or into a vein or veins. Introduction of the drug directly into venous circulation results in 100% bioavailability due to an absence of the absorption phase, provides a precise and continuous mode of drug therapy, especially for drugs with a narrow therapeutic index.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a vessel or vessels.

Concepts.definition: The administration of an agent within a vessel or vessels.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the vagina.

Concepts.definition: Administration within the vagina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the distal portion of the small intestine, from the jejunum to the cecum.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the distal portion of the small intestine, from the jejunum to the cecum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Intrahepatic route of drug administration is a method of drug delivery within the liver, predominantly via hepatic vein or artery. Regimen might be more beneficial then systemic one by delivering a higher dose of drug to the liver and reducing overall systemic exposure.

Concepts.definition: Intrahepatic route of drug administration is a method of drug delivery within the liver, predominantly via hepatic vein or artery. Regimen might be more beneficial then systemic one by delivering a higher dose of drug to the liver and reducing overall systemic exposure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The administration of a drug within or introduced directly into a tumor. Method allows to achieve high concentration of the agent in the tumor and delay drug release in systemic circulation.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within or introduced directly into a tumor. Method allows to achieve high concentration of the agent in the tumor and delay drug release in systemic circulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the uterus.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the uterus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the auris media.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug directly into the tympanic cavity has high safety profile and allows delivering high concentrations of the agent to the inner ear end organ. Perfusion is performed under the surgical microscope by inserting the needle in the posterior-inferior aspect of the tympanic membrane.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the tubules of an organ.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the tubules of an organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug within the thorax (internal to the ribs).

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the thorax (internal to the ribs).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the cerebrospinal fluid at any level of the cerebrospinal axis, including injection into the cerebral ventricles.

Concepts.definition: Administration of drugs directly into spinal subarachnoid space in the cerebrospinal fluid, at any level of the cerebrospinal axis, including injection into the cerebral ventricles, in order to bypass the blood-brain barrier and achieve local, rapid effects on the meninges or cerebrospinal axis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the thalamus.

Concepts.definition: Administration within the thalamus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the testicle.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the testicle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a tendon.

Concepts.definition: The administration of an agent within a tendon. The route is used for local therapy in various conditions of the tendinous or bursal structures such as tendinitis, tenosynovitis, epicondylitis, etc. Depending on indications and the drug, injection could be done into the tendon sheath or into the substance of the tendon.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the synovial cavity of a joint.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug within the synovial cavity of a joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the site of surgery.

Concepts.definition: Administration within the site of surgery.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration into a stoma.

Concepts.definition: Administration into a stoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug into the vagina. The medication usually has the form of a solution, tablet, cream, gel, or suppository. The drug is slowly absorbed through the vaginal wall with predominantly local, but some systemic effects.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug into the vagina. The medication usually has the form of a solution, tablet, cream, gel, or suppository. The drug is slowly absorbed through the vaginal wall with predominantly local, but some systemic effects.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug directly into the urethra.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug directly into the urethra.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug into the ureter.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug into the ureter.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The route of drug administration is unknown.

Concepts.definition: The route of drug administration is unknown.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Route of administration has not yet been assigned.

Concepts.definition: Route of administration has not yet been assigned.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug across or through the tympanic cavity. This method reduces the total dose of medication, and allows high concentrations of drug to be delivered directly to the target tissue, while reducing systemic effects. Transtympanic medication can be administered through a needle puncture of the eardrum. If multiple injections are required, a myringotomy tube can be inserted.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug across or through the tympanic cavity. This method reduces the total dose of medication, and allows high concentrations of drug to be delivered directly to the target tissue, while reducing systemic effects. Transtympanic medication can be administered through a needle puncture of the eardrum. If multiple injections are required, a myringotomy tube can be inserted.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug through the wall of the trachea.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug through the wall of the trachea.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug to an embryo in utero via systemic administration of the substance to the pregnant mother. Drugs cross the placenta through passive diffusion, active transport, pinocytosis and filtration. The properties of drugs that determine placental transfer by passive diffusion include molecular weight, pKa, lipid solubility and protein binding. Drugs with molecular weight of over 500 D are transferred incompletely. Drug metabolism and uptake can be altered by placental enzymes.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug to an embryo in utero via systemic administration of the substance to the pregnant mother. Drugs cross the placenta through passive diffusion, active transport, pinocytosis and filtration. The properties of drugs that determine placental transfer by passive diffusion include molecular weight, pKa, lipid solubility and protein binding. Drugs with molecular weight of over 500 D are transferred incompletely. Drug metabolism and uptake can be altered by placental enzymes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a substance to the mucosa; often resulting in systemic action due to absorption.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance to the mucosa; often resulting in systemic action due to absorption.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration by ingestion of colostrum or breast milk.

Concepts.definition: Administration into the body through colostrum or milk.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a substance through the dermal layer of the skin into the systemic circulation by diffusion.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance through the dermal layer of the skin into the systemic circulation by diffusion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the gingivae.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the gingivae.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the stomach.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the stomach, e.g. via gavage or via gastrostomy.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the esophagus.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the esophagus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the epidermis.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the superficial epithelial layer of the skin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within or beneath the dura.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within or beneath the dura mater.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the duodenum.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the duodenum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the duct of a gland.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the duct of a gland.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a disc.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within a fibrocartilaginous intervertebral disc.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the dermis.

Concepts.definition: Intradermal injection is a method of drug administration within the substance of the skin, particularly the dermis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the dilatable spaces of the corporus cavernosa of the penis.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the dilatable venous spaces of the cavernous tissue of the penis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the coronary arteries.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the coronary arteries supplying blood to the tissues of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug within a portion of a tooth which is covered by enamel and which is separated from the roots by a slightly constricted region known as the neck.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within a crown of tooth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the cornea (the transparent structure forming the anterior part of the fibrous tunic of the eye).

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the eye cornea.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the cisterna magna cerebellomedularis.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug directly into the cerebrospinal fluid of the brain ventricles. It could be performed by direct injection into the cisterna magna or via permanently positioned tube.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the cerebrum.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the cerebrum, directly into brain tissue, usually by injection or direct application.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug within any natural, non-pathologic cavity, such as that of cervix, uterus, or penis.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within any natural, non-pathologic cavity, such as that of cervix, uterus, or penis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a drug within a pathologic cavity.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within a pathologic cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the cauda equina.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the cauda equina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a cartilage; endochondral.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within a cartilage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the heart.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a substance by injection directly into the anterior chamber of the eye.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a medicinal product directly into the anterior chamber of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a bursa.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within a bursal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a bronchus.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug within a bronchus or bronchi. The intrabronchial drug delivery can be used for both local and systemic drug action.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the bile, bile ducts or gallbladder.

Concepts.definition: Administration within the biliary system for selective delivery of the agent to targeted hepatobiliary tissues and cell types, the goal of which is utilization of optimal therapeutic dosages combined with a reduction in systemic toxicity. Strategies for improving the tissue specificity include the use of tissue-specific ligands and the focal administration of drugs. Focal delivery has been primarily directed at uptake by the hepatocyte basolateral membrane and has included direct intraparenchymal injection, portal venous infusion, hepatic arterial infusion, and surgical systems for temporarily isolating the liver from the vasculature.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within a joint.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug within a joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within an artery or arteries.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a substance directly into an artery.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the amnion.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug within the amnion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The application of a drug to a certain area of the skin or mucous membrane (including the intra-organ application), or other tissue locally, so that the agent will take effect on the surface and/or on the underlying tissues.

Concepts.definition: The application of a drug to a certain area of the skin or mucous membrane (including the intra-organ application), or other tissue locally, so that the agent will take effect on the surface and/or on the underlying tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration above the choroid.

Concepts.definition: Administration above the choroid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration by injection through the membrane covering the muscles and nerves at the back of the eyeball.

Concepts.definition: Administration by injection through the membrane covering the muscles and nerves at the back of the eyeball.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration beneath the retina.

Concepts.definition: Administration beneath the retina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration beneath the mucous membrane.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug beneath the mucous membrane.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration beneath the tongue.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug beneath the tongue. The route provides rapid absorption, the drug immediately enters the bloodstream without first passing through the intestinal wall and liver. However, most drugs cannot be taken this way because they may be absorbed incompletely or erratically.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration beneath the skin; hypodermic. Synonymous with the term SUBDERMAL.

Concepts.definition: Drug administration beneath the skin. It provides for relatively slow, sustained release of the drug. The rate of absorption into the blood is perfusion-limited, proportional to the amount of drug at the site and can be enhanced by chemical or physical stimulation of blood flow. Subcutaneous administration minimizes the risks associated with intravascular injection: for subcutaneous infusions, external and implantable pumps are used.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration beneath the conjunctiva.

Concepts.definition: The introduction of a substance beneath the conjunctiva.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration beneath the arachnoid.

Concepts.definition: The introduction of a substance beneath the arachnoidal membrane

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration into any soft tissue.

Concepts.definition: The introduction of a substance into any soft tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration behind the pons or behind the eyeball.

Concepts.definition: The introduction of a substance behind the pons or behind the eyeball.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a substance in the form of a gas, aerosol, or fine powder via the respiratory tract, usually by oral or nasal inhalation, for local or systemic effect.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance in the form of a gas, aerosol, or fine powder via the respiratory tract, usually by oral or nasal inhalation, for local or systemic effect.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The introduction of a substance into the gastrointestinal tract by the way of the rectum, usually for systemic action. Depending on the molecular structure, drugs cross the rectal wall via either intercellular or tight junctions interconnecting the mucosal cells. Drug absorption is usually around 50% of normal oral dose. Due to the drainage pattern of the rectal veins, the hepatic first-pass effect tends to increase as the dosage form is placed deeper into the rectum. Solid suppositories represent greater than 98% of all rectal dosage forms.

Concepts.definition: The introduction of a substance into the gastrointestinal tract by the way of the rectum, usually for systemic action. Depending on the molecular structure, drugs cross the rectal wall via either intercellular or tight junctions interconnecting the mucosal cells. Drug absorption is usually around 50% of normal oral dose. Due to the drainage pattern of the rectal veins, the hepatic first-pass effect tends to increase as the dosage form is placed deeper into the rectum. Solid suppositories represent greater than 98% of all rectal dosage forms.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration into the area surrounding a vein. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: Administration into the area surrounding a vein. (NCI)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration that results in substances passing into tissue spaces or into cells.

Concepts.definition: Route of drug administration that results in substances passing into tissue spaces or intracellularly.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration through hemodialysate fluid.

Concepts.definition: Method of administering the drug through hemodialysate fluid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Drug administration outside of the body. Concept refers to a number of techniques and procedures including extracorporeal photopheresis, ultraviolet blood irradiation and extracorporeal detoxification methods with drug administration, etc.

Concepts.definition: Drug administration outside of the body. Concept refers to a number of techniques and procedures including extracorporeal photopheresis, ultraviolet blood irradiation and extracorporeal detoxification methods with drug administration, etc.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to the outside of the membrane enveloping the fetus.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug to the outside of the membrane enveloping the fetus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of the drug in the epidural space, usually at the lumbar level of the spine. The drug must initially cross the dura mater before exerting its effect on the nervous system components. The drug is also subject to uptake into the rich epidural plexus of veins. Uptake and distribution after epidural administration resembles that seen after intramuscular injection. The portion of drug that is not taken into the vascular compartment is available to cross the dura. Hydrophilicity is a major component in the pharmacokinetics of drug transfer into the subdural space.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug in the epidural space, usually at the lumbar level of the spine. The drug must initially cross the dura mater before exerting its effect on the nervous system components. The drug is also subject to uptake into the rich epidural plexus of veins. Uptake and distribution after epidural administration resembles that seen after intramuscular injection. The portion of drug that is not taken into the vascular compartment is available to cross the dura. Hydrophilicity is a major component in the pharmacokinetics of drug transfer into the subdural space.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a substance by the way of the gastrointestinal tract, usually for systemic action. Drug bioavailability can be affected due to enzymatic degradation by intestinal tissues and microbes, and first-pass hepatic metabolism.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance by the way of the gastrointestinal tract, usually for systemic action. Drug bioavailability can be affected due to enzymatic degradation by intestinal tissues and microbes, and first-pass hepatic metabolism.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Endotracheal drug administration involves the introduction of the agent directly through the endotracheal tube in an intubated patient. Generally this route is considered as a last resort for drug administration, and provides a fast, effective means of drug delivery in a patient who requires immediate medication. Plasma levels obtained via endotracheal administration are considerably less than those obtained with an equal dosage administered intravenously or intraosseously. Endotracheal administration must be followed by hyper-insufflation of the lungs to promote optimal drug absorption.

Concepts.definition: Endotracheal drug administration involves the introduction of the agent directly through the endotracheal tube in an intubated patient. Generally this route is considered as a last resort for drug administration, and provides a fast, effective means of drug delivery in a patient who requires immediate medication. Plasma levels obtained via endotracheal administration are considerably less than those obtained with an equal dosage administered intravenously or intraosseously. Endotracheal administration must be followed by hyper-insufflation of the lungs to promote optimal drug absorption.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the nasal sinuses of the head.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug within the nasal sinuses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the canal of the cervix uteri. Synonymous with the term intracervical.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug within the canal of the cervix uteri.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of drug by way of diffusion, through a membrane in an electric field. Electro-osmosis describes the active transport of non-ionized solutes associated with the bulk flow of fluid in the direction of the counter-ions that occurs with iontophoretic transport of other, ionized solutes. Using this method, even a neutral compound can be administered. Method can be used for local and systemic drug delivery.

Concepts.definition: Administration of drug by way of diffusion, through a membrane in an electric field. Electro-osmosis describes the active transport of non-ionized solutes associated with the bulk flow of fluid in the direction of the counter-ions that occurs with iontophoretic transport of other, ionized solutes. Using this method, even a neutral compound can be administered. Method can be used for local and systemic drug delivery.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration by way of food stuff.

Concepts.definition: Administration by way of food stuff.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of the drug to a tooth or teeth.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug to a tooth or teeth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to the skin.

Concepts.definition: Administration to the skin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to the conjunctiva, the delicate membrane that lines the eyelids and covers the exposed surface of the eyeball.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug to the conjunctiva, the most frequently used mode of ocular drug delivery. Advantages of this topical route include direct, localized delivery to the target tissue, good accessibility into the intraocular environment owing to membrane permeability and large intercellular spaces, avoidance of hepatic first-pass metabolism, convenience, and relative painlessness. Limitations include rapid drug elimination due to lacrimation and nasolacrimal drainage, drug binding to, and metabolism by, tear proteins, and target non-specificity as a result of systemic absorption through the nasal mucosa and conjunctival vasculature.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration directed toward the cheek, generally from within the mouth.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance through the mucosal membrane on the inside of the cheek or the back of the mouth. Buccal route bypasses first pass metabolism and avoids pre-systemic elimination in the gastrointestinal tract. The buccal environment is well supplied with both vascular and lymphatic drainage and is well suited for a retentive device. This is a feasible alternative for systemic delivery of orally inefficient drugs, such as peptide and protein drug molecules.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration within the abdomen.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug within the abdominal cavity, typically as a loco-regional therapy for disease confined to the abdomen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to or in the interstices of a tissue.

Concepts.definition: Drug administration to or in the interstices of a tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to or by way of the ear.

Concepts.definition: Administration of the drug to or by way of the ear. The drug action is mostly topical/local.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration around a tooth.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance within the tissues surrounding a tooth or teeth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration surrounding a nerve or nerves.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance within the tissues surrounding a nerve or nerves.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration to the outside of the dura mater of the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: The administration of a drug via injection or infusion into the epidural space, the area immediately adjacent to the outside surface of the dura mater of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration around a joint.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance within the tissues surrounding a joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration through the skin.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug by the way of absorption through the skin, usually for systemic action. The route allows sustained therapeutic plasma drug levels and avoids first pass effect. Simplicity of administration tends to result in high patient compliance.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a substance by some other means than through the gastrointestinal tract: usually through injection, infusion, or implantation. Predominantly, the drug action is systemic, but in some cases, it is confined to local area.

Concepts.definition: Administration of a substance by some means other than through the gastrointestinal tract: usually through injection, infusion, or implantation. Predominantly, the drug action is systemic, but in some cases, it is confined to local area.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration directly to the mouth and pharynx..

Concepts.definition: Administration of a drug directly to the mouth and pharynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Administration of a medicinal product to the oral cavity to obtain either a systemic or a local effect.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The introduction of a substance to the mouth or into the gastrointestinal tract by the way of the mouth, usually for systemic action. It is the most common, convenient, and usually the safest and least expensive route of drug administration, but it uses the most complicated pathway to the tissues and bioavailability varies. The disadvantages of method are hepatic first pass metabolism and enzymatic degradation of the drug within the gastrointestinal tract. This prohibits oral administration of certain classes of drugs especially peptides and proteins.
